clauses.clause:
The expected results of this directive are as follows:  



    The Government of Canada has the workforce capacity it needs to deliver digital services in accordance with the objectives of the 

      Policy on Service and Digital

    ;

  Departments apply a cohesive, consistent approach to talent sourcing that bridges and balances the various requirements associated with human resources, procurement, finance and operations, and is in line with central guidance;
  Departments have the data needed to enable evidence-based decisions on talent management and workforce development;
  Departments are supported in meeting digital talent requirements through government-wide guidance, business intelligence, services and tools; and
  The Government of Canadaâs digital community demonstrates measurable progress in diversity, inclusion, and equity advancement in the areas of recruitment, retention, development, and career progression.

Departmental CIOs and senior designated officials responsible for IT, cybersecurity, digital, data, or service, in collaboration with heads of human resources, senior designated officials for the management of procurement and other departmental officials as appropriate, are responsible for the following:
Taking TBS-OCIO guidance on generic roles and levels into account when determining requirements related to the recruitment and appointment of digital talent and the establishment of organizational structures;
Enabling managers to leverage flexibilities as allowed by legislation, policies, and standards, including those outlined in Mandatory Procedures on Digital Talent , to plan for, develop, and source the talent necessary to deliver digital services in a timely way;
Ensuring managers, human resources officials and contracting authorities, to whom responsibility is assigned or authority is delegated, are familiar with the requirements in this Directive and in the Mandatory Procedures on Digital Talent ;and
Balancing risk as a cohesive whole, meaning that the risk of applying certain flexibilities or solutions is carefully weighed against the impact of failing to deliver digital services.

            These procedures apply to any person whose primary or contracting function supports the development or delivery of Government of Canada (GC) digital initiatives, products or services. For the purpose of these procedures, digital talent does not refer to those supporting other mandate areas whose daily work requires the use of digital skills and tools. For the purpose of these procedures, scope of digital talent includes: 



any employee that is classified in the IT group;

any person whose primary work function is or is expected to be covered under the mandate authorities of the Chief Information Officer of Canada, including all chief information officers and heads of information technology (IT), but not including corporate support functions, such as administrative professionals and finance;

cybersecurity;

information management;

data management for the development or delivery of a GC digital initiative, service or product;

data science and analytics for the development or delivery of a GC digital initiative, service or product; and

userâexperience research or service design for the development or delivery of a GC digital initiative, service or product.
